# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-drinker-cope
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] The **meridian 100° west** of the Prime Meridian of Greenwich is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] The 100th meridian west forms a great circle with the 80th meridian east.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] In the United States, this meridian roughly marks the boundary between the semi-arid climate in the west and the humid continental and humid subtropical climates in the east, and as such roughly connotes the regions of the Eastern and the Western United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] In the United States the meridian 100° west of Greenwich forms the eastern border of the Texas panhandle with Oklahoma (which traces its origin to the Adams-Onís Treaty in 1819 which settled the border between New Spain and the United States between the Red River and Arkansas River).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] Dodge City, Kansas lies exactly at the intersection of the Arkansas River and the 100th meridian.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] As first noted by John Wesley Powell in the 1870s, there is a big difference in rainfall by the different sides of the meridian.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] West of the meridian, raising livestock is much more economically important than east of it, and what agriculture does exist relies heavily on irrigation.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] Historically, the meridian has often been taken as a rough boundary between the eastern and western United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] White settlement, spreading westward after the American Civil War, settled the area around this meridian during the 1870s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/100th-meridian-west] Highway 30 in Cozad, Nebraska, marks the place where the 100th meridian intersects with the routes of the Oregon Trail, Pony Express, transcontinental railroad, and the Lincoln Highway.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] Shull was born in Miami County, Ohio to Harrison and Catherine Ryman Shull.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] Two of his siblings included Charles Albert Shull (1879–1962) who became a professor of plant physiology and George Harrison Shull (1874–1954) who became professor of botany and genetics.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] Another brother was the botanical illustrator James Marion Shull (1872–1948).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He grew up on the family farm, learning first hand about agriculture and plants.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] After an informal early schooling, he received an AB from the University of Michigan in 1908 and briefly joined the Michigan Biological Survey.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He then joined Columbia University where he became interested in heredity, inspired by T.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He examined the influence of environmental factors on development.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He received a PhD in 1911 and became a zoology instructor at the University of Michigan.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He began to examine sex determination in rotifers and conducted experiments on mutation induction and crossing in *Drosophila*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He also conducted experiments on insect biology and took a special interest in polymorphisms such as in the presence or absence of wings in aphids.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] Shull was a critical opponent of suggestions on mimetic relationships based on human visual observation.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] McAtee showed from stomach contents of birds that mimics and models were eaten in proportion to their availability.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He believed that care needed to be taken to examine the predator and their perception.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He was an evolutionist but believed that many of the contemporary researchers were too descriptive and lacking rigour in their claims.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] In his teaching he believed that there had to be specific principles including cell organization, genetics, systematics and distribution rather than merely descriptions of "type specimens".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] He also believed that a purely historical approach to teaching biology did not help unify the field.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] Shull married zoologist Margaret Jeffrey Buckley, who was an instructor at Grinnell College in Iowa.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/aaron-franklin-shull] They had four children, including the geneticist Elizabeth Shull Russell, who later worked at the Jackson Laboratory and was elected to the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The **Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University**, formerly the **Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia**, is the oldest natural science research institution and museum in the Americas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was founded in 1812, by many of the leading naturalists of the young American republic with an expressed mission of "the encouragement and cultivation of the sciences".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] It has sponsored expeditions, conducted original environmental and systematics research, and amassed natural history collections containing more than 17 million specimens.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy also organizes public exhibits and educational programs for both schools and the general public.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] During the first decades of the United States, Philadelphia was the cultural capital and one of the country's commercial centers.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the city's institutions, the Library Company and the American Philosophical Society, were centers of enlightened thought and scientific inquiry.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The increasing sophistication of the earth and life sciences, combined with a growing awareness of the variety of life and landscape in the American wilderness, led a small group of naturalists to establish the Academy of Natural Sciences in the winter of 1812.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The academy was meant to foster a gathering of fellow naturalists and to nurture the growth and credibility of American science.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] They frequently looked to their European counterparts for inspiration and expertise and longed to be regarded as equals.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] On 25 April 1817 they were incorporated into the society under the title of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia by the legislature of Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1 January 1818, eight members were published.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2011, the Academy became affiliated with nearby Drexel University and changed its name to the Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Within a decade of its founding, the Academy became the undisputed center of natural sciences in the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy members were frequently enlisted to participate in national surveys of the western territories and other major expeditions.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Thomas Jefferson of Virginia, John Edwards Holbrook of South Carolina, Thomas Nuttall and Richard Owen of the United Kingdom, Georges Cuvier of France, and Alexander von Humboldt of Prussia were among the corresponding members (members who lived far from Philadelphia) of the Academy's first decades.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later during the 19th century, other notable naturalists and scientists, including John James Audubon, Charles S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, John Cassin, Edward Drinker Cope, Ezra Townsend Cresson, Richard Harlan, Ferdinand V.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, John Lawrence LeConte, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, George Ord, and James Rehn were members.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Corresponding members included Charles Darwin along with his supporters Asa Gray, and Thomas Henry Huxley.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] For much of its history, new members had to be nominated by two current members and then elected by the remaining members.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] These requirements were dropped in 1924.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable 20th-century scientists include James Böhlke, James Bond, Henry Weed Fowler, Ruth Patrick, Henry Pilsbry, H.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy of Natural Sciences holds an internationally important natural history collection.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, there are over 18 million biological specimens, and hundreds of thousands of volumes, journals, illustrations, photographs, and archival items in its library.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] These collections were obtained through multiple means, including the donation or purchase of existing collections or individual items, the collection activities of Academy-sponsored expeditions, or those of individual scientists, whether or not they work at the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some collections were originally gathered by other institutions.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a number of the natural history collections at the American Philosophical Society were relocated to the Academy by the end of the 19th century.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Traditionally, researchers at natural science (or natural history) institutions such as the Academy engaged in biological taxonomy, the science of discovering, describing, naming, and classifying species.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, research has shifted in emphasis to the science of systematics, the study of the evolutionary relationships among these species.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy preserves many type specimens, the reference material that helps establish a species' identity.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] They also preserve additional specimens with which scientists can investigate the nature of these species, their relationships with other species, their evolutionary history, or their conservation status.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's collections include a wide range of specimens across the tree of life.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also maintains several historically important collections.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Botany is study of plants, including nonvascular bryophytes (mosses, liverworts, and hornworts) and vascular plants, including ferns, conifers and flowering plants.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The field of botany has also traditionally included the study of algae, lichens, and fungi which are now classified in different biological kingdoms.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Collections at the Academy, which are housed in the Philadelphia Herbarium (PH), the oldest institutional herbarium in the New World, include some of the oldest and most important botanical collections in the Americas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable early collectors include Benjamin Smith Barton, Constatine Rafinesque, Thomas Meehan, Thomas Nuttall, and Fredrick Pursh.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains approximately 1.5 million specimens of vascular plants, fungi, lichens, algae, and fossil plants, 40,000 of which are types.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also contains some special collections, including the plants collected by Johann and Georg Forster during the voyages of Captain James Cook, and by Meriwether Lewis during the Lewis and Clark expedition (Corps of Discovery).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department's current focus is plant biodiversity and evolution focusing on Apocynaceae (milkweed or dogbane family) and Polygalaceae.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's Diatom Herbarium, the largest in the Americas and the second largest in the world, contains approximately 220,000 slides of these microscopic algae.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains many specimens contributed by notable collectors, a diversity of fossil diatoms, and diatoms collected as part of numerous freshwater environmental surveys in the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Diatom Herbarium also provides collections and taxonomic services for the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Former curators of note include Charles S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, Ruth Patrick, and Charles Reimer.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Entomology has been important to the Academy since its founding.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of its earliest members include Thomas Say, regarded as the father of American entomology, and Titian Peale, a leading natural history illustrator and the chief naturalist on the United States Exploring Expedition (1834–1842).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The entomology collection currently contains more than 3.5 million specimens and includes the Titian Peale Moth and Butterfly Collection, the oldest entomology collection in the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, Daniel Otte, an expert on Orthoptera (crickets, grasshoppers, and their relatives) is a pioneer of presenting biological data on the internet through the creation of the Orthoptera Species File.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator and Entomology Department Chair, Jon Gelhaus is a leading expert on crane flies and manages the Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Ichthyology has also been a part of Academy collections and research since its beginnings, but the size of the collection was relatively modest until acquisition of Edward Drinker Cope's personal collections in 1898.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] A few years later, Henry Weed Fowler began his tenure at the Academy, during which he systematized the collections and described 1,408 species.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke, William Saul, and William Smith-Vaniz are among the scientists who followed Fowler.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, John Lundberg, an expert in catfishes, pioneered deep channel collecting in large tropical rivers and is the lead author of a seminal scientific paper on the biological and geographic history of the Amazon River Basin.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ichthyology collection, which currently houses nearly 1.2 million specimens and nearly 3,000 types, is one of the most important such collections in the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department also hosts the All Catfish Species Inventory (a comprehensive online resource on catfish) and Catfish Bones (an online digital atlas of catfish morphology), and is a participant in Neodat II (an online resource of Neotropic ichthyology collections).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the early members of the Academy, Thomas Say and Isaac Lea, were malacologists (see also conchologists).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tucker Abbott, Samuel Stehman Haldeman, Henry A.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tryon, Jr. were other noted malacologists who worked at the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's malacology collection is the oldest such collection in the United States and is the 3rd largest in the world.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] It currently contains over 10 million specimens, including types erected by more than 400 authors.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Gary Rosenberg, an expert on Jamaican land snails, is a leader in digitised museum collections and research data.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research websites include the Malacology Georeferencing Project an online database of Western Atlantic Marine Mollusca (Malacolog) Archived September 24, 2015, at the Wayback Machine, and the OBIS Indo-Pacific Mollusc database.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research associate and former curator Danielle Graf, an expert on Unionidae (freshwater mussels), maintains the MUSSEL Project web site.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The majority of ornithologists active in the United States during the first half of the 19th century, including Charles Lucien Bonaparte, George Ord, Titian Ramsay Peale, John James Audubon, John Cassin, Thomas Nuttall, and John Kirk Townsend, were active members of the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later notable Academy ornithologists include James Bond, Frank Gill, Rodolphe Meyer de Schauensee, Pete Myers, Fred Sheldon, and Witmer Stone.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] With nearly 200,000 specimens representing over 9,000 species, the Ornithology collection is one of the largest and most taxonomically complete bird collections in the world.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Delaware Valley Ornithological Club (DVOC) has held regular meetings at the Academy since 1890.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Vertebrate paleontology in the United States originated in Philadelphia through the efforts of naturalists and scientists associated with the American Philosophical Society (APS) during the first decade of the 19th century and at The Academy of Natural Sciences thereafter.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] By the end of the 19th century, the holdings from the APS, including the Thomas Jefferson Fossil Collection, had been transferred to the Academy for safekeeping.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, the collection contains more than 22,000 specimens, including many types.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Richard Harlan was an early member who introduced many American naturalists to the groundbreaking works of Georges Cuvier.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Joseph Leidy, who described *Hadrosaurus* and alerted the scientific world to the paleontological treasures of the American West, is considered the "father" of American vertebrate paleontology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Edward Drinker Cope, who also worked extensively on other vertebrates, is best known for his rivalry with Othniel Charles Marsh during the infamous Bone Wars.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Daeschler is currently studying the evolution of Devonian tetrapods, but he will be retiring in September 2023.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] He is a co-discoverer of the transitional "fishapod" *Tiktaalik roseae* from the Canadian Arctic and the discoverer of two tetrapods, *Hynerpeton* and *Densignathus* from the Catskill Formation in Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy houses several collections of smaller size yet historical and scientific importance.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The general invertebrate collection contains about 22,600 specimens, while the invertebrate paleontology collection contains about 105,000 lots.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Generally, 21,500 specimens are gaunt, 13,500 are affiliated skins, and 1,700 are wet-preserved specimens.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Myers Rotifer Collection is the most comprehensive collection of rotifers on microslides.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herpetology collection contains about 40,000 specimens, including more than 500 type specimens.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The mammalogy collection contains about 36,000 specimens and 180 holotypes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Among the naturalists and scientists associated with these collections are Timothy Conrad, Edward Drinker Cope, Richard Harlan, John Edwards Holbrook, William W.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, Henry Charles Lea, Isaac Lea, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, and Thomas Say.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Formerly the Limnology Department, the Patrick Center for Environmental Research focuses on applied ecology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Founded in 1947 by Ruth Patrick, formerly of the Diatom Herbarium, it was one of the earliest U.S. environmental consulting concerns.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its attachment to the Academy led it to become the first to employ interdisciplinary teams of scientists to study freshwater systems and the first to regard biodiversity as a central criterion of water quality.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its 1948 biological survey of the Conestoga River Basin in Pennsylvania, a milestone in environmental research, led to similar surveys and studies throughout much of the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Characteristically, these earlier projects were joint projects of the Limnology Department and private industry.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since the rise of the environmental movement in the 1960s and 1970s and the resulting increases in governmental regulation of water pollution, the environmental assessments pioneered at the Academy are increasingly conducted by private environmental consulting firms.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of the work employs most of the center's expertise and capabilities, such as recent studies on the ecological effects of small dams or the ecological benefits of riparian reforestation.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other studies may involve only one or a couple of the research programs.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a current project sampling sediment cores in tidal marshes throughout the Delaware Estuary.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] This undertaking, possibly the most comprehensive core sampling in any estuary, relies extensively on the center's expertise in biogeochemistry and phycology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Once the sampling is completed, scientist will be able to investigate historical trends in marsh development, carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus cycling, water pollution, salinity variations, and climatic change by analysing the core's sediments, chemistry, and diatom assemblages.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Biogeochemistry Section of the Patrick Center is concerned with the influence of aquatic organisms on the sources, fate and transport of chemicals in aquatic systems.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies frequently deal with the carbon and nutrient cycling as well as those of trace elements (e.g., lead, copper, mercury, and zinc) and organic contaminants such as polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The section regularly provides water, sediment and tissue analyses for government, intergovernmental agencies, and private companies from around the country.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to the sediment core project mentioned above, it has recently studied the effects of small dams on sediment contaminants, photochemical transformation of marsh-derived dissolved organic matter, and sedimentation and eutrophication in salt marshes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ecological Modeling Section employs sophisticated and rigorous mathematical modelling techniques to address a variety of questions in basic and applied research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Examples include watershed-scale modeling and risk assessment; nonlinear population models structured by age, body size, or space; particle transport in turbulent aquatic systems; and the ecology and control of exotic invasive plants in urban parks.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Fisheries Section of the Patrick Center conducts research into the ecology, conservation, and management of lotic and estuarine fishes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies may range from the analysis of fish tissues for contaminants, monitoring fish populations for environmental assessments, to investigating the life histories of individual species.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Benthic macroinvertebrates (primarily aquatic insects, crustaceans, and mollusks) are useful for biological monitoring programs.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Their varied life spans, ranging from weeks to years, are long enough to reveal intermittent and continuous pollutants, yet short enough respond to worsening or improving water quality.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Macroinvertebrate Section at the Patrick Center has extensive experience in bioassessment, biomonitoring, and inventorying of freshwater habitats throughout the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Because of their great diversity and specific ecological requirements, algae, particularly diatoms, make excellent indicators of water quality.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Moreover, diatoms are readily preserved in sediments, which make them useful organisms for studying paleolimnology (the long-term trends of streams and lakes).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Phycology Section of the Patrick Center provides algal analyses for governmental and other agencies interested in both assessing water quality and long-term environmental trends.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] One such undertaking is the analyses of diatom assemblages in lake sediments (sediment cores) throughout the eastern United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] This work, part of a large project managed by the EPA, will try to establish reference (pre-anthropogenic) conditions for lakes throughout the country.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to these research efforts, the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center has developed a set of online resources Archived September 6, 2019, at the Wayback Machine for using algae in environmental research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] These include an algal image database, autecology datasets for freshwater algae, algae research with the USGS National Water-Quality Assessment (NAWQA) program, and a diatom paleolimnology database.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] For most of its history, biological taxonomy and systematics were conducted using comparative morphology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, however, advances in molecular biology and computational technologies have opened new possibilities for studying the diversity and history of life through the use of cladistics and computational phylogenetics.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] These technologies also offer new opportunities for molecular ecology and conservation genetics.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy scientists have been early adapters of molecular biology techniques.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Allozymes, DNA-DNA hybridization, immunoelectrophoresis, restriction site analyses of mitochondrial DNA and serology were used extensively since the late 1960s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent molecular work mainly employs DNA sequencing, microsatellites, and AFLP (amplified fragment length polymorphism).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2004, the Laboratory for Molecular Systematics and Ecology (LMSE) was formed as a shared, multi-user facility to improve access to and provide training for the use of molecular data in systematic and ecological research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to supporting staff, the lab offers research opportunities for students and post-doctoral fellowships.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's work in Mongolia started with the realization of the unique research opportunities available at Lake Hovsgol (Hovsgol Nuur).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] This large lake and its watershed were remarkably pristine and relatively unknown, especially in comparison to its sister lake in Russia, Lake Baikal.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, a multidisciplinary team of scientists from the Academy, as well as from other American institutions, Mongolia, Russia, and Japan started a multi-year study of the lake's biodiversity, limnology, and watershed.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Although this research was scientifically rewarding, it was apparent that issues concerning environmental protection and sustainable economic development needed addressing.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Consequently, work at Hovsgol shifted to ecosystem studies and capacity building.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] One early undertaking was the enhancement of the operational and physical infrastructure at Hovsgol National Park.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Long-term ecological monitoring of several tributary watersheds began in 1997 and soon the site would be adopted into the International Long Term Ecological Research Network.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent work at Hovsgol is focusing on the consequences of and sustainable responses to climate change.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The region lies in a transitional zone between the semi-arid Eurasian Steppe (grasslands) to the south and the Eurasian Taiga (boreal forest) to the north.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] As such, it is an ideal mid-continental site at which to monitor the ecological effects of climate change.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, changes in livestock herding practices raise concerns about overgrazing and desertification.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In response, the team at Hovsgol created and distributed a *Herder Handbook* and continues to conduct research and work with nomadic herders to develop sustainable practices.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey is a multi-year biodiversity survey, environmental monitoring and capacity building project managed by Jon Gelhaus of the Academy's Entomology Department.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] A total of 217 sites from the Selenge River Basin, the most populous and most extensive drainage in Mongolia, were surveyed from 2003 to 2006.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Most of these sites are in rivers or streams, but some are in freshwater and saltwater lakes, hot and cold springs, and marsh wetlands.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Additional sites from the remote drainage systems in western Mongolia will be sampled in 2008.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The survey has yielded numerous new species and hundreds of geographic records for known aquatic insects, provided an extensive dataset for ongoing environmental monitoring, and has helped develop research and technical infrastructures in Mongolia.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] This capacity building includes, in collaboration with the Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology, the building of the first research laboratory in Mongolia dedicated to the study of aquatic invertebrates.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also includes training of Mongolian scientists and students.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Center for Environmental Policy informs and engages various constituents, promotes solutions, and builds public and professional awareness on important environmental topics.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Much of its activities focus on public programs and working groups.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center hosts or participates in a number of public programs that are free and open to the public.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Urban Sustainability Forums feature panels of local and national experts discussing environmental and sustainability topics as they relate to the Philadelphia region.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Town Square, which may feature a panel or an individual, addresses a variety of topics relating to the environment or public science.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center also hosts candidate forums, conferences and workshops.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center acts as a logistical hub for a number of Working Groups organized around sustainability issues.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently active groups include one for condominium and building co-op owners, a network of faith-based environmental groups, and a forum of senior executives in the private sector.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Library and Archives were established at the Academy's founding meeting in 1812 for the purpose of supporting its natural science research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library provides online access, services, collections, imaging, and shared resources with other libraries.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library houses nearly 200,000 volumes ranging from works published in the 16th century to current journals and books.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its holdings also include illustrated works from as early as the 15th century, including Konrad Gessner's *Historia animalium*, Maria Sibylla Merian's *Insects of Surinam*, Edward Lear's *Psittacidae or Parrots*, and a double elephant folio of John James Audubon's *The Birds of America*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences* was the first peer-reviewed publication in the United States devoted to the natural sciences.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1842, it had been superseded by the *Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Proceedings* have been published continuously since 1841.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal* was reborn in 1847 as a larger-format publication that could accommodate longer articles and monographs.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy publishes three other series.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The occasional series *Notulae Naturae* began in 1939 as a means to quickly publish short items, usually not longer than 16 pages on subject areas such as zoology, botany, ecology, geology and paleontology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Monographs* series, which began in 1935, is composed principally of larger systematic reviews of selected taxonomic groups.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Special Publications* series, begun in 1922, includes works such as biography, taxonomy, historical reviews, and collections surveys.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO (VIsual REsource for Ornithology) is the most comprehensive collection of bird images in the world.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Started in 1979, the collection contains over 180,000 photographs representing over 7,300 species.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The collection contains work by some of the world's most talented photographers.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO licenses bird images for a wide variety of commercial and non-profit uses.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy first opened its collections to the public in 1828.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The popularity of its exhibits soared in 1868 with the debut of the world's first mounted dinosaur skeleton, *Hadrosaurus*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The size of the crowds flocking to this display prompted the Academy to relocate to its present-and roomier-location in 1876.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] As with most museums in the 19th century, there was little separation of the Academy's collections, which were vital to scientific work, and the public spaces.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Not only did this subject the collections to extra wear and tear, but visitors were typically confronted with a bewildering assemblage of specimens with little in the way of supplemental information.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Over time, however, museums such as the Academy started to showcase their more popular specimens while sequestering the bulk of the collections.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, they spent more effort interpreting their public displays.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Museums started to play a more active role in educating the public.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] One expression of this transformation was the rise of that icon of natural history museums, the diorama.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] These three-dimensional displays were the virtual reality of their time, providing generations of museum visitors with their only opportunity to experience distant places and exotic wildlife.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green created The Academy's first diorama, depicting rocky mountain goats.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green's work was at first controversial amongst The Academy's staff, due to both the cost and accusations of sensationalism, but proved popular amongst the public.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1935, the Works Progress Administration began providing artists to help work on the dioramas, fueling the exhibits' continued expansion.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] By presenting the wilderness to the public, dioramas nurtured an appreciation of our natural heritage, which, coincided with the growth of the Conservation Movement in the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy currently has 37 dioramas, most of which were installed in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] They feature a variety of animals from Africa, Asia, and North America.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of these, such as the caribou, lion, and plains zebra are familiar and relatively common, but others, such as the desert bighorn, kiang, Kodiak bear, panda, and passenger pigeon, are threatened, endangered, or extinct.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2018, under the management of Drexel University, The Academy renovated some of the older dioramas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] These renovations were meant to increase the scientific accuracy of the displays and improve their aesthetics.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Another icon of natural history museums is the dinosaur skeleton.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The first of these, the *Hadrosaurus* mount created by noted natural history artist Benjamin Waterhouse Hawkins, made its debut at the Academy in 1868.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] *Hadrosaurus* mounts also found their way into other public venues, including Princeton University, the Royal Scottish Museum, the Smithsonian, and the 1876 American Centennial Exposition.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] A special exhibit on the history of *Hadrosaurus foulkii* ran from November 22, 2008 to April 19, 2009.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] A skeletal mount of a related dinosaur, *Corythosaurus*, served as the centerpiece of the Academy's "Hall of Earth History" during the middle of the 20th century.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1986, the Academy opened a new exhibit, "Discovering Dinosaurs".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] This was the first large-scale exhibit to incorporate the findings of the "dinosaur renaissance".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Instead of cold-blooded and lumbering reptiles, dinosaurs were conceived as active-and possibly warm-blooded-animals more akin to birds than reptiles.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, another type of dinosaur was the subject of an exhibition at the academy when it featured Jim Gary's Twentieth Century Dinosaurs and found that it was an enormous success with the public.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, the academy also opened "Outside-In", a hands-on children's nature museum.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, it pioneered the hands-on simulation of a dinosaur dig, with its "The Big Dig".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other permanent exhibits include "Secrets of the Diorama", an insight into what goes into a diorama, and "Science at the Academy", which showcases current Academy research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also has special, changing exhibits.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent changing exhibits include "Skin: Living Armor, Evolving Identity", "Illuminating Birds", "Extreme Deep: Mission to the Abyss", and "Crocs: Ancient Predators in a Modern World".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Four weekend festivals organized around scientific disciplines, are held during the year.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Paleopalooza, held in mid-February, features fossil collections and talks by leading paleontologists.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Earth Day Festival, held in mid-April, features scientists from the Academy's Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Bug Fest, held in mid August, features entomologists, insect collections and live insects.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Philadelphia Shell Show, held in mid-October, features an international shell market and competitive shell displays.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy began offering lectures to the public as early as the 1820s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Current offerings include natural history author talks, lectures by scientists, workshops and classes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, the Center for Environmental Policy produces public programs on environmental issues.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its Nature Club in the 1930s, the Academy has offered programming just for children.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Several programs appropriate for different age groups are currently offered.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Safari Overnight sleepovers (camp-ins) are held on selected weekends during Fall, Winter, and Spring.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts can participate in day workshops and sleepovers to fulfill badge and pin requirements.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tiny Tot Explorers is a program for toddlers.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] A new series of Family Workshops designed for both adults and children was launched in early 2010.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Wild Weekends", held on selected weekends throughout the year, offer a variety of children's programs, including hands-on exploration of museum specimens, crafts and live animal shows with mammals, birds and reptiles.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Live animal shows are also presented at regular times on other days and featured prominently in the educational programs.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Field trips to the Academy are available throughout the year for schools, summer camps and other groups.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Optional directed programs include Discovery Lessons for younger age groups (pre-K and higher) and Science Explorers for older children (grades 7 through 9).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Academy on the Go" is an educational outreach program that visits schools, camps, and community centers.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] WINS (Women in Natural Sciences) is an innovative and successful science enrichment program conducted by The Academy of Natural Sciences in collaboration with the School District of Philadelphia.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its founding in 1982, WINS has been providing female public school students with hands-on science classes, scientific literacy and skill-building activities, and opportunities for personal growth in a uniquely nurturing setting.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy Explorers Camp is a day camp program offered during Spring Break and the Summer.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The George Washington Carver Science Fair is held in February or March.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Science fair participants are eligible for the George Washington Carver Scholars summer program, which is also held at the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Educator workshops are held throughout the year.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The most recent series covered the integration of science and literacy skills.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Self-guided workbooks tailored for younger children are available for some of the museum exhibits.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Hayden Memorial Geological Award is given to prominent scientists working in geology or paleontology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1888 in memory of Ferdinand V.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Hayden, a distinguished American geologist and pioneering surveyor of the American West who had extensive ties to the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Established in 1980, the Gold Medal for Distinction in Natural History Art is awarded to people whose artistic endeavors and life's work have contributed to our understanding and appreciation of living things.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Richard Hopper Day Memorial Medal, established in 1960 by his granddaughter, Margaret Day Dilks, is awarded in recognition of outstanding contributions in interpreting the natural sciences to the public.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Joseph Leidy Award honors research in the natural sciences.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1923 as a tribute to the many contributions and long association of Joseph Leidy with the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Böhlke Memorial Endowment Fund honors the memory of James E.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke who were prominent ichthyologists at the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] This fund provides support for graduate students and recent postdoctoral researchers to work with the Ichthyology Collection and the Academy's Library.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Gallagher Fellowship provides a unique opportunity for original, multi-year, postdoctoral or sabbatical research on the systematics of microscopic invertebrates, especially Rotifera.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The research focus must be on systematics and may employ ecological, behavioral, physiological, molecular or developmental tools.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jessup and McHenry Awards are competitively awarded to students wishing to conduct studies at the postgraduate, doctoral and postdoctoral levels under the supervision or sponsorship of a member of the curatorial staff of the Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Jessup Award is given for any specialty in which our curators have expertise.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The McHenry Fund is restricted to botanists.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Eckelberry Endowment helps support the efforts of wildlife painters, sculptors, printmakers, and other artists to better acquaint themselves with the natural world through both museum and field research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, artistic and scientific mentors counsel and assist these artists as their careers develop.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope had little formal scientific training, and he eschewed a teaching position for field work.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He made regular trips to the American West, prospecting in the 1870s and 1880s, often as a member of U.S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] A personal feud between Cope and paleontologist Othniel Charles Marsh led to a period of intense fossil-finding competition now known as the Bone Wars.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's financial fortunes soured after failed mining ventures in the 1880s, forcing him to sell off much of his fossil collection.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He experienced a resurgence in his career toward the end of his life before dying on April 12, 1897.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Though Cope's scientific pursuits nearly bankrupted him, his contributions helped to define the field of American paleontology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He was a prodigious writer with 1,400 papers published over his lifetime, although his rivals debated the accuracy of his rapidly published works.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He discovered, described, and named more than 1,000 vertebrate species, including hundreds of fishes and dozens of dinosaurs.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Edward Drinker Cope was born on July 28, 1840, the eldest son of Alfred and Hanna Cope.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The death of his mother when he was three years old seemed to have had little effect on young Edward, as he mentioned in his letters that he had no recollection of her.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His stepmother Rebecca Biddle filled the maternal role; Cope referred to her warmly, as well as his younger stepbrother, James Biddle Cope.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Alfred, an orthodox member of the Religious Society of Friends or Quakers, operated a lucrative shipping business started by his father Thomas P.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He was a philanthropist who gave money to the Society of Friends, the Philadelphia Zoological Gardens and the Institute for Colored Youth.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Edward was born and raised in a large stone house called "Fairfield", whose location is now within the boundaries of Philadelphia.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The 8 acres (3.2 ha) of pristine and exotic gardens of the house offered a landscape that Edward was able to explore.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The Copes began teaching their children to read and write while very young, and took Edward on trips across New England and to museums, zoos, and gardens.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's interest in animals became apparent at a young age, as did his natural artistic ability.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Alfred intended to give his son the same education he himself had received.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] At age nine, Edward was sent to a day school in Philadelphia; at 12, he attended the Friends' Boarding School at Westtown, near West Chester, Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The school was founded in 1799 with fundraising by members of the Society of Friends (Quakers), and provided much of the Cope family's education.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The prestigious school was expensive, costing Alfred $500 in tuition each year, and in his first year, Edward studied algebra, chemistry, scripture, physiology, grammar, astronomy, and Latin.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Edward's letters home requesting a larger allowance show he was able to manipulate his father, and he was, according to author and Cope biographer Jane Davidson, "a bit of a spoiled brat".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His letters suggest he was lonely at the school—it was the first time he had been away from his home for an extended period.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Otherwise, Edward's studies progressed much like a typical boy—he consistently had "less than perfect" or "not quite satisfactory" marks for conduct from his teachers, and did not work hard on his penmanship lessons, which may have contributed to his often-illegible handwriting as an adult.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Edward returned to Westtown in 1855, accompanied by two of his sisters.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Biology began to interest him more that year, and he studied natural history texts in his spare time.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] While at the school, he frequently visited the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Edward often obtained bad marks due to quarreling and bad conduct.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His letters to his father show he chafed at farm work and betrayed flashes of the temper for which he would later become well known.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] After sending Edward back to the farm for summer break in 1854 and 1855, Alfred did not return Edward to school after spring 1856.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Instead, Alfred attempted to turn his son into a gentleman farmer, which he considered a wholesome profession that would yield enough profit to lead a comfortable life, and improve the undersized Edward's health.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Until 1863, Cope's letters to his father continually expressed his yearning for a more professional scientific career than that of a farmer, which he called "dreadfully boring".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] While working on farms, Edward continued his education on his own.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1858, he began working part-time at the Academy of Natural Sciences, reclassifying and cataloguing specimens, and published his first series of research results in January 1859.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope began taking French and German classes with a former Westtown teacher.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Though Alfred resisted his son's pursuit of a science career, he paid for his son's private studies.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Instead of working the farm his father bought for him, Edward rented out the land and used the income to further his scientific endeavors.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Alfred finally gave in to Edward's wishes and paid for university classes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope attended the University of Pennsylvania in the 1861 and/or 1862 academic years, studying comparative anatomy under Joseph Leidy, one of the most influential anatomists and paleontologists at the time.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope asked his father to pay for a tutor in German and French to allow him to read scholarly works in those languages.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] During this period, he had a job recataloging the herpetological collection at the Academy of Natural Sciences, where he became a member at Leidy's urging.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope visited the Smithsonian Institution on occasion, where he became acquainted with Spencer Baird, who was an expert in the fields of ornithology and ichthyology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1861, he published his first paper on Salamandridae classification; over the next five years he published primarily on reptiles and amphibians.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's membership in the Academy of Natural Sciences and American Philosophical Society gave him outlets to publish and announce his work; many of his early paleontological works were published by the Philosophical Society.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1863 and 1864, during the American Civil War, Cope traveled through Europe, taking the opportunity to visit the most esteemed museums and societies of the time.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Initially, he seemed interested in helping out at a field hospital, but in letters to his father later on in the war, this aspiration seemed to disappear; instead he considered working in the American South to assist freed African Americans.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Davidson suggests Cope's correspondence with Leidy and Ferdinand Hayden, who worked as field surgeons during the war, might have informed Cope of the horrors of the occupation.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Edward was involved in a love affair; his father did not approve.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Whether Edward or the unnamed woman (whom he at one point intended to marry) broke off the relationship is unknown, but he took the breakup poorly.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Biographer and paleontologist Henry Fairfield Osborn attributed Edward's sudden departure for Europe as a method of keeping him from being drafted into the Civil War.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope did write to his father from London on February 11, 1864, "I shall get home in time to catch and be caught by the new draft.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] I shall not be sorry for this, as I know certain persons who would be mean enough to say that I have gone to Europe to avoid the war." Eventually, Cope took the pragmatic approach and waited out the conflict.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He may have suffered from mild depression during this period, and often complained of boredom.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In the winter of 1863, Edward met Othniel Charles Marsh while in Berlin.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh, age 32, was attending the University of Berlin.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He held two university degrees in comparison to Edward's lack of formal schooling past 16, but Edward had written 37 scientific papers in comparison to Marsh's two published works.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] While they would later become rivals, the two men appeared to take a liking to each other upon meeting.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh led Edward on a tour of the city, and they stayed together for days.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] After Edward left Berlin, the two maintained correspondence, exchanging manuscripts, fossils, and photographs.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Edward burned many of his journals and letters from Europe upon his return to the United States.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Friends intervened and stopped Cope from destroying some of his drawings and notes, in what author Url Lanham deemed a "partial suicide".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] When Cope returned to Philadelphia in 1864, his family made every effort to secure him a teaching post as the Professor of Zoology at Haverford College, a small Quaker school where the family had philanthropic ties.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The college awarded him an honorary master's degree so he could have the position.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The two had a single daughter, Julia Biddle Cope, born June 10, 1866.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's return to the United States also marked an expansion of his scientific studies; in 1864, he described several fishes, a whale, and the amphibian *Amphibamus grandiceps* (his first paleontological contribution).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] During the period between 1866 and 1867, Cope went on trips to western parts of the country.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He related to his father his scientific experiences; to his daughter he sent descriptions of animal life as part of her education.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope found educating his students at Haverford "a pleasure", but wrote to his father that he "could not get any work done." He resigned from his position at Haverford and moved his family to Haddonfield, in part to be closer to the fossil beds of western New Jersey.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Due to the time-consuming nature of his Haverford position, Cope had not had time to attend to his farm and had let it out to others, but eventually found he was in need of more money to fuel his scientific habits.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Pleading with his father for money to pursue his career, he finally sold the farm in 1869.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Alfred apparently did not press his son to continue farming, and Edward focused on his scientific career.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He continued his continental travels, including trips to Virginia, Tennessee, and North Carolina.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He stopped these cave explorations after an 1871 trip to the Wyandotte Caves in Indiana, but remained interested in the subject.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope had visited Haddonfield many times in the 1860s, paying periodic visits to the marl pits.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The fossils he found in these pits became the focus of several papers, including a description in 1868 of *Elasmosaurus platyurus* and *Laelaps*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh accompanied him on one of these excursions.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's proximity to the beds after moving to Haddonfield made more frequent trips possible.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The Copes lived comfortably in a frame house backed by an apple orchard.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Two maids tended the estate, which entertained a number of guests.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's only concern was for more money to spend on his scientific work.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The 1870s were the golden years of Cope's career, marked by his most prominent discoveries and rapid flow of publications.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Among his descriptions were the therapsid *Lystrosaurus* (1870), the archosauromorph *Champsosaurus* (1876), and the sauropod *Amphicoelias* (1878).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In the period of one year, from 1879 to 1880, Cope published 76 papers based on his travels through New Mexico and Colorado, and on the findings of his collectors in Texas, Kansas, Oregon, Colorado, Wyoming, and Utah.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] During the peak years, Cope published around 25 reports and preliminary observations each year.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The hurried publications led to errors in interpretation and naming—many of his scientific names were later canceled or withdrawn.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In comparison, Marsh wrote and published less frequently and more succinctly—his works appeared in the widely read *American Journal of Science,* which led to faster reception abroad, and Marsh's reputation grew more rapidly than Cope's.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In autumn 1871, Cope began prospecting farther west to the fossil fields of Kansas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Leidy and Marsh had been to the region earlier, and Cope employed one of Marsh's guides, Benjamin Mudge, who was in want of a job.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's companion Charles Sternberg described the lack of water and good food available to Cope and his helpers on these expeditions.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The severe desert conditions and Cope's habit of overworking himself till he was bedridden caught up with him, and in 1872, he broke down from exhaustion.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope maintained a regular pattern of summers spent prospecting and winters writing up his findings from 1871 to 1879.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Throughout the decade, Cope traveled across the West, exploring rocks of the Eocene in 1872 and the Titanothere Beds of Colorado in 1873.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1874, Cope was employed with the Wheeler Survey, a group of surveys led by George Montague Wheeler that mapped parts of the United States west of the 100th meridian.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The survey traveled through New Mexico, whose Puerco formations, he wrote to his father, provided "the most important find in geology I have ever made".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The New Mexico bluffs contained millions of years of formation and subsequent deformation, and were in an area which had not been visited by Leidy or Marsh.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Being part of the survey had other advantages; Cope was able to draw on fort commissaries and defray publishing costs.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] While there was no salary, his findings would be published in the annual reports the surveys printed.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope brought Annie and Julia along on one such survey, and rented a house for them at Fort Bridger, but he spent more of his own money on these survey trips than he would have liked.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Alfred died December 4, 1875, and left Edward with an inheritance of nearly a quarter of a million dollars.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Alfred's death was a blow to Cope; his father was a constant confidant.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The same year marked a suspension of much of Cope's field work and a new emphasis on writing up discoveries of the previous years.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His chief publication of the time, *The Vertebrata of the Cretaceous Formations of the West*, was a collection of 303 pages and 54 illustration plates.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The memoir summarized his experiences prospecting in New Jersey and Kansas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope now had the finances to hire multiple teams to search for fossils for him year-round and he advised the Philadelphia Centennial Exhibition on their fossil displays.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's studies of marine reptiles of Kansas closed in 1876, opening a new focus on terrestrial reptiles.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The same year, Cope moved from Haddonfield to 2100 and 2102 Pine Street in Philadelphia.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He converted one of the two houses into a museum where he stored his growing collection of fossils.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's expeditions took him across Kansas, Colorado, New Mexico, Wyoming, and Montana.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His initial journey into the Clarendon beds of Upper Miocene and Lower Pliocene of Texas led to an affiliation with the Geological Survey of Texas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's papers on the region constitute some of his most important paleontological contributions.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1877, he purchased half the rights to the *American Naturalist* to publish the papers he produced at a rate so high, Marsh questioned their dating.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope returned to Europe in August 1878 in response to an invitation to join the British Association for the Advancement of Science's Dublin meeting.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He was warmly welcomed in England and France, and met with the distinguished paleontologists and archeologists of the period.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh's attempts to sully Cope's reputation had made little impact on anyone save paleontologist Thomas Henry Huxley, who according to Osborn, "alone treated [Cope] with coolness".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Following the Dublin meeting, Cope spent two days with the French Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] At each gathering, Cope exhibited dinosaur restorations by Philadelphia colleague John A.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Ryder and various charts and plates from geological surveys of the 1870s led by Ferdinand Vandeveer Hayden.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He returned to London on October 12, meeting with anatomist Richard Owen, ichthyologist Albert Günther, and paleontologist H.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] While in Europe, Cope purchased a great collection of fossils from Argentina.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope never found time to describe the collection and many of the boxes remained unopened until his death.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's relations with Marsh turned into a competition for fossils between the two, known today as the Bone Wars.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The conflict's seeds began upon the men's return to the United States in the 1860s, although Cope named *Colosteus marshii* for Marsh in 1867, and Marsh returned the favor, naming *Mosasaurus copeanus* for Cope in 1869.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope introduced his colleague to the marl pit owner Albert Vorhees when the two visited the site.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh went behind Cope's back and made a private agreement with Vorhees: any fossils that Vorhees's men found were sent back to Marsh at New Haven.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was outraged and the two argued for some time until they agreed to have Leidy examine the bones and determine who was right.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Leidy came, picked up the head of the fossil and put it on the other end.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was horrified since he had already published a paper on the fossil with the error at the American Philosophical Society.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He immediately tried to buy back the copies, but some remained with their buyers (Marsh and Leidy kept theirs).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The whole ordeal might have passed easily enough had Leidy not exposed the cover-up at the next society meeting, not to alienate Cope, but only in response to Cope's brief statement where he never admitted he was wrong.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope and Marsh would never talk to each other amicably again, and by 1873, open hostility had broken out between them.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The rivalry between the two increased towards the latter half of the 1870s.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1877, Marsh received a letter from Arthur Lakes, a schoolteacher in Golden, Colorado.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Lakes had been hiking in the mountains near the town of Morrison with his friend, H.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Beckwith, looking for fossilized leaves in the Dakota sandstone.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Instead, the pair found large bones embedded in the rock.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Lakes wrote that the bones were "apparently a vertebra and a humerus bone of some gigantic saurian." While Lakes sent Marsh some 1,500 pounds of bone, he also sent Cope some of the specimens.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh published his finds first, and having been paid $100 for the finds Lakes wrote to Cope that the samples should be forwarded to Marsh.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Meanwhile, Cope received bones from school superintendent O.W.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Lucas in March 1877 from Cañon City; the remains were of a dinosaur even bigger than Lakes' that Marsh had described.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Word that Lakes had notified Cope of his finds galvanized Marsh into action.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] When Marsh heard from Union Pacific Railroad workers W.E.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Reed about a vast boneyard northwest of Laramie in Como Bluff, Marsh sent his agent, Samuel Wendell Williston, to take charge of the digging.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope, in response, learned of Carlin and Reed's discoveries and sent his own men to find bones in the area.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The two scientists attempted to sabotage each other's progress.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was described as a genius, yet what Marsh lacked in intelligence, he easily made up for in connections—Marsh's uncle was George Peabody, a rich banker who supported Marsh with money, and a secure position at the Peabody Museum.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh lobbied John Wesley Powell to act against Cope and attempted to persuade Hayden to "muzzle" Cope's publishing.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Both men tried to spy on the other's whereabouts and attempted to offer their collectors more money in the hopes of recruiting them to their own side.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was able to recruit David Baldwin in New Mexico and Frank Williston in Wyoming from Marsh.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope and Marsh were extremely secretive as to the source of their fossils.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] When Henry Fairfield Osborn, at the time a student at Princeton University, visited Cope to ask where to travel to look for fossils in the West, Cope politely refused to answer.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] When Cope arrived back in the United States after his tour of Europe in 1878, he had nearly two years of fossil findings from Lucas.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Among these dinosaurs was *Camarasaurus*, one of the most recognizable dinosaur recreations of the time.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The summer of 1879 took Cope to Salt Lake City, San Francisco, and north to Oregon, where he was amazed at the rich flora and the blueness of the Pacific Ocean.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1879, the United States Congress consolidated the various government survey teams into the United States Geological Survey with Clarence King as its leader.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] This was discouraging to Cope because King named Marsh, an old college friend, as the chief paleontologist.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The period of Cope's and Marsh's paleontological digs in the American West spanned from 1877 to 1892, by which time both men exhausted much of their financial resources.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh's close association with the Geological Survey gave him the resources to employ 54 staff members over the course of ten years.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His teaching position at Yale meant he had guaranteed access to the *American Journal of Science* for publication.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope had his interest in the *Naturalist*, but it drained him of funds.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] After Hayden was removed from the survey, Cope lost his source of government funding.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His fortune was not enough to support his rivalry, so Cope invested in mining.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Most of his properties were silver mines in New Mexico; one mine yielded an ore vein worth $3 million in silver chloride.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope visited the mines each summer from 1881 to 1885, taking the opportunity to supervise or collect other minerals.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] For a while he made good money, but the mines stopped producing and by 1886 he had to give up his now-worthless stocks.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The same year he received a teaching position at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He continued to travel west, but realized he would not be able to best Marsh in cornering the market for bones; he had to release the collectors he had hired and sell his collections.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] During this period, he published 40 to 75 papers each year.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] With the failure of his mines, Cope began searching for a job, but was turned down at the Smithsonian and American Museum of Natural History.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He turned to giving lectures for hire and writing magazine articles.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Each year, he lobbied Congress for an appropriation with which to finish his work on "Cope's Bible", a volume on Tertiary vertebrates, but was continually turned down.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Rather than work with Powell and the survey, Cope tried to inflame sentiment against them.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] At Marsh's urging, Powell pushed for Cope to return specimens he had unearthed during his employment under the government surveys.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] This was an outrage to Cope, who had used his own money while working as a volunteer.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In response, Cope went to the editor of the *New York Herald* and promised a scandalous headline.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Since 1885, Cope had kept an elaborate journal of mistakes and misdeeds that both Marsh and Powell had committed over the years.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] From scientific errors to publishing mistakes, he had them written down in a journal he kept in the bottom drawer of his Pine Street desk.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope sought out Marsh's assistants, who complained of being denied access and credit by their employer and of being chronically underpaid.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Reporter William Hosea Ballou ran the first article on January 12, 1890, in what would become a series of newspaper debates between Marsh, Powell, and Cope.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope attacked Marsh for plagiarism and financial mismanagement, and attacked Powell for his geological classification errors and misspending of government-allocated funds.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Marsh and Powell published their own side of the story and, in the end, little changed.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] No congressional hearing was created to investigate Powell's alleged misallocation of funds, while Cope and Marsh were not held responsible for any mistakes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Indirectly, however, the attacks may have been influential in Marsh's fall from power in the survey.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Due to pressure from Powell over bad press, Marsh was removed from his position for the government surveys.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's relations with the president of the University of Pennsylvania soured, and the entire funding for paleontology in the government surveys was pulled.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope took his sinking fortunes in stride.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In writing to Osborn about the articles, he laughed at the outcome, saying, "It will now rest largely with you whether or not I am supposed to be a liar and am actuated by jealousy and disappointment.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] I think Marsh is impaled on the horns of *Monoclonius sphenocerus*." Cope was well aware of his enemies and was carefree enough to name a species after a combination of "Cope" and "hater", *Anisonchus cophater*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Through his years of financial hardship, he was able to continue publishing papers—his most productive years were 1884 and 1885, with 79 and 62 papers published, respectively.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The 1880s marked the publication of two of the best-known fossil taxa described by Cope: the pelycosaur *Edaphosaurus* in 1882 and the early dinosaur *Coelophysis* in 1889.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1889, he succeeded Leidy, who had died the previous year, as professor of zoology at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The small yearly stipend was enough for Cope's family to move back into one of the townhouses he had been forced to relinquish earlier.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1892, Cope (then 52 years old) was granted expense money for field work from the Texas Geological Survey.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] With his finances improved, he was able to publish a massive work on the *Batrachians of North America*, which was the most detailed analysis and organization of the continent's frogs and amphibians ever mastered, and the 1,115-page *The Crocodilians Lizards and Snakes of North America*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In the 1890s, his publication rate increased to an average of 43 articles a year.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His final expedition to the West took place in 1894, when he prospected for dinosaurs in South Dakota and visited sites in Texas and Oklahoma.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The same year, Julia was married to William H.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Collins, a Haverford astronomy professor.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The couple's ages—Julia was 28 and the groom 35—were past the conventions of Victorian marriage.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] After their European honeymoon, the couple returned to Haverford.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] While Annie moved to Haverford, as well, Cope did not.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His official reason was the long commute and late lectures he gave in Philadelphia.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In private correspondence, however, Osborn wrote that the two had essentially separated, though they remained on amiable terms.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope sold his collections to the American Museum of Natural History in 1895; his set of 10,000 American fossil mammals sold for $32,000, lower than Cope's asking price of $50,000.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The purchase was financed by the donations from New York's high society.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope sold three other collections for $29,000.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] While his collection contained more than 13,000 specimens, Cope's fossil hoard was still much smaller than Marsh's collection, valued at over a million dollars.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The University of Pennsylvania bought part of Cope's ethnological artifact collection for $5,500.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia's foremost museum, did not bid on any of Cope's sales due to bad blood between Cope and the museum's leaders; as a result, many of Cope's major finds left the city.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's proceeds from the sales allowed him to rehire Sternberg to prospect for fossils on his behalf.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1896, Cope began suffering from a gastrointestinal illness he said was cystitis.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His wife cared for him in Philadelphia when she was able; at other times, Cope's university secretary, Anna Brown, tended to him.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope at this time lived in his Pine Street museum and rested on a cot surrounded by his fossil finds.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope often prescribed himself medications, including large amounts of morphine, belladonna, and formalin, a substance based on formaldehyde used to preserve specimens.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Osborn was horrified by Cope's actions and made arrangements for surgery, but the plans were put on hold after a temporary improvement in Cope's health.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope went to Virginia looking for fossils, became ill again, and returned to his home very weak.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Osborn visited Cope on April 5, inquiring about Cope's health, but the sick paleontologist pressed his friend for his views on the origin of mammals.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Word of Cope's illness spread, and he was visited by friends and colleagues; even in a feverish condition Cope delivered lectures from his bed.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope died on April 12, 1897, 16 weeks short of his 57th birthday.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Sternberg, still prospecting for Cope that spring, was woken by a liveryman who relayed word from Annie that Cope had died three days earlier.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The coffin was loaded on a hearse and carried to a gathering at Fairfield; much of the gathering was spent in silence.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] After the coffin was removed, the assembled began talking.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope gave his family a choice of his books, with the remainder to be sold or donated to the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] After debts were handled, Cope left small bequests to friends and family—Anna Brown and Julia received $5,000 each, while the remainder went to Annie.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's estate was valued at $75,327, not including additional revenue raised by sales of fossils to the American Museum of Natural History, for a total of $84,600.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Some specimens preserved in alcohol made their way to the Academy of Natural Sciences, including a few Gordian worms.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope insisted through his will that no graveside service or burial be held; he had donated his body to science.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He issued a final challenge to Marsh at his death: he had his skull donated to science so his brain could be measured, hoping his brain would be larger than that of his adversary; at the time, brain size was thought to be the true measure of intelligence.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Osborn listed Cope's cause of death as uremic poisoning, combined with a large prostate, but the true cause of death is unknown.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Many believed Cope had died of syphilis contracted from the women with whom he fraternized during his travels.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1995, Davidson gained permission to have the skeleton examined by a medical doctor at the university.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Morrie Kricun, a professor of radiology, concluded no evidence of bony syphilis was found on Cope's skeleton.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Public mentions of Cope's death were relatively slight.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The *Naturalist* ran four photographs, a six-page obituary by editor J.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Kingsley, and a two-page remembrance by Frazer.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The National Academy of Sciences' official memoir was submitted years later and written by Osborn.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The *American Journal of Science* devoted six paragraphs to Cope's passing, and incorrectly gave his age as 46.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was outlived by his rival Marsh, who was suffering poor health.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Julia assisted Osborn in writing a biography of her father, titled *Cope: Master Naturalist*.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] She would not comment on the name of the woman with whom her father had had an affair prior to his first European travel.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Julia is believed to have burned any of the scandalous letters and journals Cope had kept, but many of his friends were able to give their recollections of the scandalous nature of some of Cope's unpublished routines.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was described by zoologist Henry Weed Fowler as "a man of medium height and build, but always impressive with his great energy and activity".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] To him, Fowler wrote, "[Cope] was both genial and always interesting, easily approachable, and both kindly and helpful." His self-taught nature, however, meant that he was largely hostile to bureaucracy and politics.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He had a famous temper; one friend called Cope a "militant paleontologist".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Despite his faults, he was generally well liked by his contemporaries.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] American paleontologist Alfred Romer wrote that, "[Cope's] little slips from virtue were those we might make ourselves, were we bolder".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was raised as a Quaker, and was taught that the Bible was literal truth.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Although he never confronted his family about their religious views, Osborn writes that Cope was at least aware of the conflict between his scientific career and his religion.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Biographer Jane Davidson believes that Osborn overstated Cope's internal religious conflicts.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] She ascribes Cope's deference to his father's beliefs as an act of respect or a measure to retain his father's financial support.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Frazer's reminiscences about his friend suggest Cope often told people what they wanted to hear, rather than his true views.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] As a young man, Cope read Charles Darwin's *Voyage of a Naturalist*, which had little effect on him.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The only comment about Darwin's book recorded by Cope was that Darwin discussed "too much geology" from the account of his voyage.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Due to his background in taxonomy and paleontology, Cope focused on evolution in terms of changing structure, rather than emphasizing geography and variation within populations as Darwin had.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Over his lifetime, Cope's views on evolution shifted.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His early views held that while Darwin's natural selection may affect the preservation of superficial characteristics in organisms, natural selection alone could not explain the formation of genera.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's suggested mechanism for this action was a "steady progressive development of organization" through what Cope termed "a continual crowding backward of the successive steps of individual development".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His position later evolved to one with an increased emphasis on continual and utilitarian evolution with less involvement of a Creator.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He became one of the founders of the Neo-Lamarckism school of thought, which holds that an individual can pass on traits acquired in its lifetime to offspring.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Although the view has been shown incorrect, it was the prevalent theory among paleontologists in Cope's time.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1887, Cope published his own "Origin of the Fittest: Essays in Evolution", detailing his views on the subject.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He was a strong believer in the law of use and disuse—that an individual will slowly, over time, favor an anatomical part of its body so much that it will become stronger and larger as time progresses down the generations.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] The giraffe, for example, stretched its neck to reach taller trees and passed this acquired characteristic to its offspring in a developmental phase that is added to gestation in the womb.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's *Theology of Evolution* (1887) argued that consciousness arose from the mind of the universe, which directed animals to new goals and forms.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Sideris, "[Cope] argued that organisms respond to changes in their environments by an exercise of choice.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Consciousness itself, he maintained, was the principal force in evolution.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's views on human races and sex were influenced by his Lamarckian beliefs, which posited those of European ancestry as more highly evolved than nonwhite groups.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He believed that if, "a race was not white then it was inherently more ape-like".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He was opposed to blacks because of their "degrading vices", believing that the "inferior Negro should go back to Africa" and that their "poor virtue" was inherent.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope was against the modern view of women's rights, believing in the husband's role as protector; he was opposed to women's suffrage, as he felt they would be unduly influenced by their husbands, and that it would lead to the retrogression of the race as women took on more "masculine" attributes.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In his career, Cope published over 1,400 scientific papers.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His major works include three volumes: *On the Origin of Genera* (1867), *The Vertebrata of the Tertiary Formations of the West* (1884) and "Essays in Evolution".
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] He discovered a total of 56 new dinosaur species during the Bone Wars compared to Marsh's 80.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Although Cope is today known as a herpetologist and paleontologist, his contributions extended to ichthyology, in which he cataloged 300 species of fishes and described over 300 species of reptiles over three decades.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In total, he discovered and described over 1,000 species of fossil vertebrates and published 600 separate titles; one species of Caribbean snake, *Liophis juliae*, he named in honor of his daughter.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His proposal for the origin of mammalian molars is notable among his theoretical contributions.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Oliver, 1938, *Dipsas copei* Günther, 1872, Cope's gray treefrog *Hyla chrysoscelis* Cope, 1880, and the splash tetra genus *Copella* G.S.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Myers, 1956 are among the many taxa named in honor of Cope.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Currently, 21 fish species named *copei* are distributed among 11 families.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope lent his name to the *Journal of the American Society of Ichthyologists and Herpetologists* (né *Copeia*) from 1913 to 2020, when the journal was renamed in light of changing attitudes towards Cope's racist views.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's Pine Street home is recognized as a national landmark.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Cope's remains are still kept as scientific specimens.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His brain was donated to the American Anthropometric Society and is still preserved in alcohol at the Wistar Institute.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His skull is at the University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] His ashes were placed at the institute with those of Leidy, while his bones were extracted and kept in a locked drawer to be studied by anatomy students.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1907, Edward Anthony Spitzka published a paper of his analysis of six brains at the American Anthropometric Society, including Cope's with additional analysis of Cope's skull.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] In 1993, the American photographer Louie Psihoyos borrowed Cope's skull and prominently incorporated it into his book *Hunting Dinosaurs* (1994).
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Psihoyos and his assistant, John Knoebber, traveled around America with Cope's skull, taking pictures of the skull in different places on the "adventure" and showing it to various modern paleontologists.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Among the notable incidents during the journey was Robert T.
[src:edward-drinker-cope/edward-drinker-cope] Bakker pouring pasta into the skull to measure Cope's brain size.
